    // So p_1 must be different from p_n unless n=1.
    // For example, if n=3, p=[1,2,3], reverse(p)=[3,2,1]. Different.
    // If p=[1,3,2], reverse(p)=[2,3,1]. Different.
    // The only way p could be equal to its reverse is if p_i = p_{n-1-i} for all i,
    // AND all elements are distinct. This is impossible for n >= 2.
    // For example, if p_1 = p_n, then p_1 and p_n are the same element,
    // which violates the distinctness property of a permutation unless n=1.
    // Since n >= 2, p_1 and p_n must be distinct elements.
    // Therefore, p is never equal to its reverse for n >= 2.
    // So, reversing the permutation always yields a different permutation with the same fingerprint.

    std::reverse(p.begin(), p.end());

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cout << p[i] << (i == n - 1 ? "" : " ");
    }
    std::cout << "\n";
}

