    // The goodness would be `(a[n-2].value + a[n-1].value) - (a[0].value + a[1].value + h)`.
    // This is the third candidate for goodness.
    //
    // This specific partition is: `a[0]` in group 1, `a[1]...a[n-1]` in group 2.
    // This is exactly what we calculated in the second `if` block.
    //
    // The three main candidates for goodness are:
    // 1. All elements in one group: `(a[n-1]+a[n-2]) - (a[0]+a[1])`
    //    Partition: all 1s (or all 2s).
    // 2. `a[0]` in group 1, `a[1]...a[n-1]` in group 2.
    //    `min_f = (n >= 3) ? std::min(a[1]+a[2], a[0]+a[1]+h) : (a[0]+a[1]+h)`
    //    `max_f = (n >= 3) ? std::max(a[n-2]+a[n-1], a[0]+a[n-1]+h) : (a[0]+a[1]+h)`
    //    Goodness = `max_f - min_f`.
    // 3. `a[n-1]` in group 1, `a[0]...a[n-2]` in group 2.
    //    `min_f = (n >= 3) ? std::min(a[0]+a[1], a[n-1]+a[0]+h) : (a[0]+a[1]+h)`
